  Challenge 007: Login Fun
  
  Approach
  
  Place a script in /etc/profile.d/ — both bash and zsh source files from this directory on interactive login. The script:
  
  1. Picks cat/dog/cow based on $UID % 3
  2. Shows previous login count via last
  3. Shows current sessions via who
  4. Shows system utilization via top -bn1 | head -5
  
  Implementation
  
  #!/bin/bash
  # /etc/profile.d/login-fun.sh
  
  # ASCII art selection based on user ID
  case $(( UID % 3 )) in
    0)
      cat << 'EOF'
    /\_/\  
   ( o.o ) 
    > ^ <
   /|   |\
  (_|   |_)
  EOF
      ;;
    1)
      cat << 'EOF'
    / \__
   (    @\___
    /         O
   /   (_____/
  /_____/   U
  EOF
      ;;
    2)
      cat << 'EOF'
   ^__^
   (oo)\_______
   (__)\       )\/\
       ||----w |
       ||     ||
  EOF
      ;;
  esac
  
  # Previous login count
  LOGIN_COUNT=$(last "$USER" | grep -c "^$USER")
  echo "Previous logins for $USER: $LOGIN_COUNT"
  echo
  
  # Currently logged in sessions
  echo "Current sessions:"
  who
  echo
  
  # System utilization (top header)
  echo "System utilization:"
  top -bn1 | head -5
  
  Setup
  
  sudo install -m 0644 login-fun.sh /etc/profile.d/login-fun.sh
  
  How it works
  
  - /etc/profile.d/ — Scripts here are sourced by /etc/profile on login shells. Bash sources /etc/profile for login shells. Zsh sources it too (when invoked as sh,
  or via /etc/zsh/zprofile on most distros which explicitly sources /etc/profile or iterates /etc/profile.d/).
  - UID % 3 — Deterministic per-user selection. UID 0 (root) always gets cat, UID 1000 (typical first user) gets cat, 1001 gets dog, 1002 gets cow, etc.
  - last "$USER" — Queries /var/log/wtmp for historical login records. grep -c counts the lines.
  - who — Shows all currently logged-in sessions (user, terminal, login time).
  - top -bn1 | head -5 — Batch mode, 1 iteration, first 5 lines give uptime, tasks, CPU%, and memory.
  
  Zsh note
  
  If the target distro's zsh doesn't source /etc/profile.d/ automatically, add a symlink or source line in /etc/zsh/zprofile:
  
  # /etc/zsh/zprofile (if not already sourcing profile.d)
  for f in /etc/profile.d/*.sh; do [ -r "$f" ] && . "$f"; done
  
  Most mainstream distros (Ubuntu, Fedora, Arch) already handle this.
